A021001.name: Pisot sequence P(2,9).
formula: Pisot sequence P(x, y): a(0) = x, a(1) = y, a(n) = roundDown(a(n-1)^2/a(n-2)) = ceiling(a(n-1)^2/a(n-2) - 1/2).

A021002.name: Decimal expansion of zeta(2)*zeta(3)*zeta(4)*...
formula: Product of A080729 and A080730. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 16 2011

A021003.name: a(n) = (n/2)*(n^4+1).
formula: a(n) = -a(-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 11 2017

A021004.name: Pisot sequence P(4,10).
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = 2a(n-1) + a(n-2) + a(n-3) - a(n-4) - a(n-6) (checked up to n = 1000)
Conjectured G.f.: (4+2 x+x^2-2 x^3-x^4-2 x^5)/(1-2 x-x^2-x^3+ x^4+x^6) - _Harvey P. Dale_, Mar 12 2011

A021005.name: Let q_k=p(p+2) be product of k-th pair of twin primes; sequence gives values of p such that (q_k)^2 > q_{k-i}q_{k+i} for all 1 <= i <= k-1.

A021006.name: Pisot sequence P(4,11), a(0)=4, a(1)=11, a(n+1) is the nearest integer to a(n)^2/a(n-1). Evidently satisfies a(n) = 2*a(n-1)+2*a(n-2).

A021007.name: Let q_k = p*(p+2) be product of k-th pair of twin primes; sequence gives values of p+2 such that (q_k)^2 > q_{k-i}*q_{k+i} for all 1 <= i <= k-1.

A021008.name: Pisot sequence P(5,11), a(0)=5, a(1)=11, a(n+1) is the nearest integer to a(n)^2/a(n-1).

A021009.name: Triangle of coefficients of Laguerre polynomials n!*L_n(x) (rising powers of x).
formula: a(n, m) = ((-1)^m)*n!*binomial(n, m)/m! = ((-1)^m)*((n!/m!)^2)/(n-m)! if n >= m, otherwise 0.
Representation (of unsigned a(n, m)) as special values of Gauss hypergeometric function 2F1, in Maple notation: n!*(-1)^m*hypergeom([ -m, n+1 ], [ 1 ], 1)/m!. - _Karol A. Penson_, Oct 02 2003
Sum_{n>=0, m>=0} a(n, m)*(x^n/n!^2)*y^m = exp(x)*BesselJ(0, 2*sqrt(x*y)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 07 2005
Matrix square yields the identity matrix: L^2 = I. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 22 2008
Symbolically, with D=d/dx and LN(n,x)=n!L_n(x), define :Dx:^j = D^j x^j, :xD:^j = x^j D^j, and LN(.,x)^j = LN(j,x) = row polynomials of A021009.
2) (xDx)^n = x^n D^n x^n = x^n LN(n,-:xD:)  [See Al-Salam ref./A132440]
3) (DxD)^n = D^n x^n D^n = LN(n,-:xD:) D^n  [See　ref. in A132440]
4) umbral composition LN(n,LN(.,x))= x^n   [See Rota ref.]
5) umbral comp. LN(n,-:Dx:) = LN(n,-LN(.,-:xD:)) = 2^n LN(n,-:xD:/2)= n! * (n-th row e.g.f.(x) of A038207 with x replaced by :xD:).
An example for 2) is the operator (xDx)^2 = (xDx)(xDx) = xD(x^2 + x^3D)= 2x^2 + 4x^3 D + x^4 D^2 = x^2 (2 + 4x D + x^2 D^2) = x^2 (2 + 4 :xD: + :xD:^2) = x^2 LN(2,-:xD:) = x^2 2! L_2(-:xD:).
An example of the umbral composition in 5) is given in A038207.

The op. xDx is related to the Euler/binomial transformation for power series/o.g.f.s. through exp(t*xDx) f(x) = f[x/(1-t*x)]/(1-t*x) and to the special Moebius/linear fractional/projective transformation z exp(-t*zDz)(1/z)f(z) = f(z/(1+t*z)).
For a general discussion of umbral calculus see the Gessel link. (End)
Standard recurrence derived from the three term recurrence of the orthogonal polynomials system {n!*L(n,x)}: L(n,x) = (2*n  - 1 - x)*L(n-1,x) - (n-1)^2*L(n-2,x), n>=1, L(-1,x) = 0, L(0,x) = 1.
n >=1, with a(n,-1) = 0, a(0,0) = 1, a(n,m) = 0 if n < m. (compare this with Peter Luschny's program for the unsigned case |a(n,m)| = (-1)^m*a(n,m)).
Simplified recurrence (using column recurrence from explicit form for a(n,m) given above):
|T(n,k)| = [x^k] (-1)^n*U(-n,1,-x), where U(a,b,x) is Kummer's hypergeometric U function. - _Peter Luschny_, Apr 11 2015
T(n,k) = (-1)^k*n!*S(n,k) where S(n,k) is recursively defined by: "if k = 0 then 1 else if k > n then 0 else S(n-1,k-1)/k + S(n-1,k)". - _Peter Luschny_, Jun 21 2017
The unsigned case is the exponential Riordan square (see A321620) of the factorial numbers. - _Peter Luschny_, Dec 06 2018

Omitting the diagonal and signs, this array is generated by the commutator [D^n,x^n] = D^n x^n - x^n D^n = sum_{i=0,n-1} ((n!/i!)^2/(n-i)!) x^i D^i on p. 9 of both papers by Belov-Kanel and Kontsevich. - _Tom Copeland_, Jan 23 2020

A021010.name: Triangle of coefficients of Laguerre polynomials L_n(x) (powers of x in decreasing order).

A021011.name: Pisot sequence P(6,11), a(0)=6, a(1)=11, a(n+1) is the nearest integer to a(n)^2/a(n-1).

A021012.name: Triangle of coefficients in expansion of x^n in terms of Laguerre polynomials L_n(x).
formula: Sum_{k>=0} T(n, k)*T(m, k) = (n+m)!. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 14 2005
Unsigned sequence = A136572 * A007318 - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jan 07 2008
A136572*PS, where PS is a triangle with PS[n,k] = (-1)^k*A007318[n,k]. PS = 1/PS. - _Gerald McGarvey_, Aug 20 2009

A021013.name: Pisot sequence P(7,11), a(0)=7, a(1)=11, a(n+1) is the nearest integer to a(n)^2/a(n-1). Agrees with A021014 only for n <= 20.

A021016.name: Decimal expansion of 1/12.
formula: Equals 1/(2*3*4) + 1/(3*4*5) + 1/(4*5*6) + 1/(5*6*7) + ... = Sum_{i > 0} 1/((i+1)*(i+2)*(i+3)). See Jolley in References, p. 48 (sum obtained from the series 268, case t = 2). - _Bruno Berselli_, Mar 29 2014

A021021.name: Expansion of 1/((1-10x)(1-11x)(1-12x)).
formula: If we define f(m,j,x) = Sum_{k=j..m} binomial(m,k)*Stirling2(k,j)*x^(m-k) then a(n-2) = f(n,2,10) for n >= 2. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 26 2009

A021026.name: Decimal expansion of 1/22.
formula: a(n)=(9/2)+[(-1)^n]/2-5*[C(2*n,n) mod 2], with n>=0 [From _Paolo P. Lava_, Mar 31 2009]

A021031.name: Decimal expansion of 1/27.
formula: a(n) = (31*(n mod 3) - 2*(n+1 mod 3) + (n+2 mod 3))/9 (cf. forms of modular arithmetic of Paolo P. Lava, i.e. see A146094). (End)

A021078.name: Decimal expansion of 1/74.
formula: a(n) = (2n-1) mod 6, for n > 0. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 23 2014

A021103.name: Number of two-connected (or biconnected) planar graphs with n nodes.

A021105.name: Decimal expansion of 1/101.
formula: E.g.f.: 9*(-sin(x) - cos(x) + sinh(x) + cosh(x))/2. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 04 2016

A021115.name: Decimal expansion of 1/111.
formula: a(n) = (9/2)*( (n-1)*n mod 3 ) = 4*(n mod 3) - 2*((n+1) mod 3) + ((n+2) mod 3), formulas suggested by _Giovanni Resta_.

A021136.name: Decimal expansion of 1/132.
formula: a(n)=6+(-1)^n-7*[C(2*n,n) mod 2]-5*{C[(n+1)^2,n+3] mod 2}, with n>=0 [From _Paolo P. Lava_, Sep 21 2009]

A021160.name: Decimal expansion of 1/156.
formula: The period is just 6: after 0.00, 641025 repeated endlessly. - _Alonso del Arte_, Apr 18 2018

A021169.name: Decimal expansion of 1/165.
formula: a(n) = 3+3*(-1)^n-6*[C(2*n,n) mod 2], with n>=0. [_Paolo P. Lava_, Sep 23 2009]

A021179.name: Decimal expansion of 1/175.
formula: Equals A021032 minus 3/100. [From _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 25 2008]

A021189.name: Decimal expansion of 1/185.
formula: a(n)=(1/3)*{4*(n mod 3)-2*[(n+1) mod 3]+7*[(n+2) mod 3]}-4*[C(2*n,n) mod 2], with n>=0 [From _Paolo P. Lava_, Sep 24 2009]

A021226.name: Decimal expansion of 1/222.
formula: a(n)=(1/3)*{2*(n mod 3)-[(n+1) mod 3]+8*[(n+2) mod 3]}-5*[C(2*n,n) mod 2], with n>=0 [From _Paolo P. Lava_, Sep 25 2009]

A021256.name: Decimal expansion of 1/252.
formula: (X^n * (1-X)^n)/n! where X=5, n=7 (see comment above). - _Douglas L. Fox_, Apr 30 2012

A021307.name: Decimal expansion of 1/303.
formula: a(n)=(1/4)*{4*(n mod 4)+[(n+1) mod 4]-2*[(n+2) mod 4]+[(n+3) mod 4]}, with n>=0 [From _Paolo P. Lava_, Nov 06 2009]

A021316.name: Decimal expansion of 1/312.
formula: a(n) = (18 - 3*cos(n*Pi/3) - 9*cos(2*n*Pi/3) + 5*sqrt(3)*sin(n*Pi/3) - 11*sqrt(3)*sin(2*n*Pi/3))/6 for n > 2 with a(0)=a(1)=0, a(2)=3. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Oct 04 2018

A021318.name: Decimal expansion of 1/314.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) - a(n-39) + a(n-40) for n > 40. - _Chai Wah Wu_, Jul 22 2020

A021408.name: Decimal expansion of 1/404.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) for n>4, a(n) = a(n-4) for n>5.

A021424.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)(1-3x)(1-5x)(1-7x)).
formula: E.g.f.: (343*exp(7*x) - 375*exp(5*x) + 81*exp(3*x) - exp(x))/48, from the e.g.f. of the fourth column (k=3) of A039755. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, May 26 2017

A021448.name: Decimal expansion of 1/444.
formula: a(n) = (n mod 3)+2*[(n+1) mod 3]-2*[C(2*n,n) mod 2]-5*{C[(n+1)^2,n+3] mod 2}, with n>=0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Nov 11 2009
a(n) = 2*((n+1) mod 3) + (n mod 3), n > 1. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 16 2014

A021499.name: Decimal expansion of 1/495.
formula: a(n) = 1 + (-1)^n - 2*(C(2*n,n) mod 2), with n>=0.  - _Paolo P. Lava_, Nov 18 2009

A021529.name: Decimal expansion of 1/525.
formula: Equals A021088 minus 1/100. [From _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 25 2008]

A021579.name: Decimal expansion of 1/575.
formula: Equals A021050 minus 0.02. [From _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 30 2009]

A021817.name: Decimal expansion of 1/813.
formula: a(n)=(n-1 mod 5) mod 4, Paolo P. Lava, Mar 14 2011.

A021823.name: Decimal expansion of 1/819.
formula: a(n+2) = sum{k=0..n, binomial(n-2k, n-k)}. - _Paul Barry_, Jan 15 2005

A021874.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)(1-4x)(1-7x)(1-10x)).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(x)*(1000*exp(9*x) - 1029*exp(6*x) + 192*exp(3*x) - 1)/(3!*3^3). This is d^3/dx^3 exp(x)*(exp(3*x - 1))^3/(3!*3^3); see also column m=3 of A282629 divided by 3^3. The o.g.f. is given in the name. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Apr 08 2017

A021913.name: Period 4: repeat [0, 0, 1, 1].
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) for n > 2. (End)
a(n+2) = Sum_{k=0..n} b(k), with b(k) = A056594(k) (partial sums of S(n,x) Chebyshev polynomials at x=0).
Euler transform of length 4 sequence [1, -1, 0, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 28 2014
a(1-n) = a(n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 28 2014

A021934.name: Decimal expansion of 1/930.
formula: A021097 shifted right. [From _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 25 2008]
